==Literature==
[[File:Jambai Tamil Brahmi.jpg|thumb|right|[[Athiyamān Nedumān Añci|Jambai Tamil Brahmi inscription]] dated to the early [[Sangam period|Sangam age]]]]
Four Dravidian languages, [[Tamil language|Tamil]], [[Kannada language|Kannada]], [[Malayalam]] and [[Telugu language|Telugu]], have lengthy literary traditions.{{sfnp|Krishnamurti|2003|p=20}}
Literature in [[Tulu language|Tulu]] and [[Kodava language|Kodava]] is more recent.{{sfnp|Krishnamurti|2003|p=20}}

The earliest known Dravidian inscriptions are 76 [[Tamil language#Old Tamil|Old Tamil]] inscriptions on cave walls in [[Madurai district|Madurai]] and [[Tirunelveli district|Tirunelveli]] districts in [[Tamil Nadu]], dating from the 2nd century BCE.{{sfnp|Krishnamurti|2003|p=22}}
These inscriptions are written in a variant of the [[Brahmi script]] called [[Tamil Brahmi]].{{sfnp|Mahadevan|2003|pp=90–95}}
The earliest long text in Old Tamil is the ''[[Tolkappiyam|Tolkāppiyam]]'', an early work on Tamil grammar and poetics, whose oldest layers could date from the 1st century BCE.{{sfnp|Krishnamurti|2003|p=22}}

